   616/// Returns list of output filenames created
   617///
   618/// This function uses trait-dispatched saving via [`ExecutionContext::save_slot`],
   619/// which delegates to each type's [`SlotPersistence`] implementation. This ensures
   620/// all slot types are handled uniformly without explicit matching for each type.
   621fn save_session_data(ctx: &ExecutionContext, primitive_name: &str, provenance: &Provenance) -> Result<Vec<String>> {
   622    let data_dir = session_data_dir();
   623    fs::create_dir_all(&data_dir)?;
   624    let mut output_files = Vec::new();
   625
   626    // Save all populated slots using trait-dispatched saving
   627    for slot in ctx.populated_slots() {
   628        let filename = ExecutionContext::slot_filename(slot);
   629        let path = data_dir.join(filename);
   630
   631        // Use trait-dispatched save - returns Ok(true) if data was saved
   632        match ctx.save_slot(slot, &path) {
   633            Ok(true) => {
   634                save_provenance_sidecar(&path, provenance)?;
   635                output_files.push(filename.to_string());
   636                tracing::info!("Saved {:?} to {}", slot, path.display());
   637            }
   638            Ok(false) => {
   639                // Slot exists but couldn't be saved (type mismatch or unsupported)
   640                tracing::debug!("Slot {:?} populated but not saveable", slot);
   641            }
   642            Err(e) => {
   643                tracing::warn!("Failed to save {:?}: {}", slot, e);
   644            }
   645        }
   646    }
   647
   648    tracing::debug!("Saved {} outputs for primitive '{}'", output_files.len(), primitive_name);
   649    Ok(output_files)
   650}

/// Emit PlotUpdated events for any plot files in the outputs
fn emit_plot_events(broadcaster: &super::events::SharedBroadcaster, outputs: &serde_json::Value) {
    // Check if outputs contains a PlotSpec
    if let Some(plot_spec) = outputs.get("PlotSpec") {
        // Extract plot info
        let plot_id = plot_spec
            .get("title")
            .and_then(|t| t.as_str())
            .map(|s| s.to_string())
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "plot".to_string());

        let plot_type = plot_spec
            .get("viz_type")
            .and_then(|t| t.as_str())
            .unwrap_or("scatter")
            .to_string();

        let point_count = plot_spec
            .get("point_count")
            .and_then(|c| c.as_u64())
            .unwrap_or(0) as usize;

        broadcaster.emit(super::events::DaemonEvent::PlotUpdated {
            plot_id,
            plot_type,
            point_count,
            timestamp: super::events::DaemonEvent::now(),
        });

        tracing::info!("Emitted PlotUpdated event");
    }

    // Also check for plot file in outputs object
    if let serde_json::Value::Object(map) = outputs {
        for (key, _value) in map {
            if key.to_lowercase().contains("plot") {
                // This output is plot-related, emit an event
                broadcaster.emit(super::events::DaemonEvent::PlotUpdated {
                    plot_id: "plot".to_string(),
                    plot_type: "scatter".to_string(),
                    point_count: 0,
                    timestamp: super::events::DaemonEvent::now(),
                });
                tracing::info!("Emitted PlotUpdated event for key: {}", key);
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}

Tool reply2025-12-20T23:34:53.951Z
     1# Visualization Architecture Specification
     2
     3> **Status**: Phase 6 ACTIVE - Migrating to ggterm-native GGSpec format
     4>
     5> This document captures architectural decisions for BioStack's visualization system.
     6>
     7> **Implementation Status**:
     8> - Phase 4 (Integration) complete
     9> - Phase 5 (Hybrid PlotSpec + Vega-Lite) complete
    10> - **Phase 6 (ggterm integration) ACTIVE** - Adopting ggterm spec as canonical format
    11>
    12> **IMPORTANT: PlotSpec Deprecation**
    13>
    14> PlotSpec (the original Rust-native plot specification) is being deprecated in favor of
    15> **GGSpec** - a Rust mirror of ggterm's Grammar of Graphics specification. This provides:
    16> - Full Grammar of Graphics expressiveness (layered geoms, stats, facets, etc.)
    17> - Direct compatibility with ggterm rendering (no conversion layer)
    18> - Richer visualization capabilities than the original point-centric PlotSpec
    19>
    20> See "Phase 6: ggterm Native Integration" below for migration details.
    21
    22---
    23
    24## Vision: Minimal Data Science Interface
    25
    26Traditional data science IDEs require:
    27- Code editor (write R/Python)
    28- File browser
    29- Variable inspector
    30- Console/terminal
    31- Plot window
    32- Notebook interface
    33
    34**BioStack vision**: Three-panel interface:
    35
    36```
    37
    38              WebGL Plots                 
    39          (visualize results)             
    40
    41  Claude Code       BioStack TUI        
    42  (conversation)    (status/tables)     
    43
    44```
    45
    46**Panel responsibilities**:
    47- **WebGL Plots** (TypeScript/React + deck.gl): High-fidelity visualization, handles millions of points
    48- **Claude Code** (raw terminal): Conversation = analysis, runs `claude` directly
    49- **BioStack TUI** (Bubble Tea/Go): Session status, data tables, primitives list, quick commands
    50
    51**Why this works**:
    52- Code editor  Gone. Claude Code writes commands.
    53- File browser  Gone. Claude Code navigates.
    54- Variable inspector  BioStack TUI shows data tables and session state.
    55- Notebook  Gone. Conversation IS the notebook.
    56- Plots  Dedicated WebGL panel for scientific visualization.
    57
    58The insight: **If LLM + intelligent types handle mechanics, humans only need conversation and results.**
    59
    60---
    61
    62## Technology Stack Decisions (December 2024)
    63
    64### WebGL Plots Panel
    65- **Framework**: TypeScript + React (fast iteration, rich ecosystem)
    66- **Rendering**: Vega-Lite via vega-embed (declarative grammar of graphics)
    67  - PlotSpec generates Vega-Lite spec via `to_vega_lite()` method
    68  - Daemon serves plot files with embedded `vega_lite_spec` field
    69  - Dramatically simplifies frontend (50 lines vs 400+ with custom rendering)
    70- **Layout**: allotment or react-mosaic (split panels)
    71- **Updates**: SSE from bioengine daemon
    72
    73> **Note**: Phase 5 moved from custom deck.gl rendering to Vega-Lite. This preserves PlotSpec's data model (provenance, queries, annotations) while delegating rendering to a well-documented standard.
    74
    75### BioStack TUI Panel
    76- **Framework**: Bubble Tea (Go)
    77- **Why Bubble Tea**:
    78  - Native clipboard via OSC52 (works over SSH!)
    79  - Rich components: bubbles, bubble-table
    80  - Powers OpenCode (proven for agentic tools)
    81  - Ratatui rejected due to copy/paste issues
    82- **Components**: bubble-table for data, spinners, lists, help
    83- **Fallback**: Textual (Python) if Bubble Tea proves problematic
    84
    85### Claude Code Panel
    86- Raw terminal running `claude` command
    87- No wrapper needed - Claude Code is already excellent
    88- Biostack skill provides context injection
    89
    90### Coordination
    91- bioengine daemon serves SSE for plot updates
    92- File-based communication (.biostack/commands/, .biostack/results/)
    93- TUI watches same files as daemon for status updates
    94
    95---
    96
    97## Core Principle: Plots Are Data
    98
    99A plot is not "output" - it's an artifact that can be:
   100- **Inspected**: "What's that outlier?"
   101- **Transformed**: "Show only significant points"
   102- **Modified**: "Add labels to top 5 genes"
   103- **Input to other operations**: "Overlay this dataset"
   104- **Tracked**: Full provenance in session graph
   105
   106Therefore, `PlotSpec` is a bioforge type like any other, with all standard traits.
   107
   108---
   109
   110## Unified Data Model
   111
   112### PlotSpec as a First-Class Type (DEPRECATED)
   113
   114>  **DEPRECATED**: PlotSpec is being replaced by GGSpec. See "Phase 6: ggterm Native Integration" below.
   115> The information here is retained for reference but new development should use GGSpec.
   116
   117```rust
   118// DEPRECATED - Use GGSpec instead
   119pub struct PlotSpec {
   120    // Identity
   121    id: Uuid,
   122    title: String,
   123    description: String,
   124
   125    // Data layer
   126    points: Vec<DataPoint>,
   127    source_artifact: String,  // What data this came from
   128
   129    // Visual encoding
   130    encoding: PlotEncoding,
   131
   132    // Decorations
   133    annotations: Vec<Annotation>,
   134}
   135
   136pub struct DataPoint {
   137    id: String,              // e.g., gene name, sample ID
   138    x: f64,
   139    y: f64,
   140    z: Option<f64>,
   141    metadata: HashMap<String, Value>,  // Original row data
   142}
   143
   144pub struct PlotEncoding {
   145    x: AxisSpec,
   146    y: AxisSpec,
   147    color: Option<ColorSpec>,
   148    size: Option<SizeSpec>,
   149    shape: Option<ShapeSpec>,
   150}
   151```
   152
   153### Standard Traits
   154
   155PlotSpec implements all intelligent type traits:
   156
   157| Trait | Purpose for Plots |
   158|-------|-------------------|
   159| `SlotPersistence` | Save/load `.plot` files |
   160| `LlmGlance` | Summary for Claude Code context |
   161| `TypeProvenance` | Track what primitive created it |
   162| `TypeQuality` | Rendering issues, outlier warnings |
   163| `TypeCapabilities` | Can modify, filter, export |
   164| `Visualizable` | Self-referential: plots visualize themselves |
   165
   166### Storage Location
   167
   168Plots live in `data/` alongside other artifacts:
   169
   170```
   171.biostack/
   172 data/
   173    counts.csv
   174    pca_results.csv
   175    pca_scatter.plot       Plot artifact
   176    volcano.plot           Plot artifact
   177 commands/
   178    pending/
   179 results/
   180 session.json               Tracks all artifacts including plots
   181```
   182
   183No separate `viz/` directory. Plots are just data.
   184
   185---
   186
   187## Visualization as Intrinsic Type Property
   188
   189Types know how to visualize themselves via the `Visualizable` trait:
   190
   191```rust
   192pub trait Visualizable {
   193    /// Default visualization for this type (if any)
   194    fn default_viz(&self) -> Option<PlotSpec>;
   195
   196    /// Alternative visualizations this type supports
   197    fn available_viz(&self) -> Vec<VizType>;
   198
   199    /// Generate specific visualization
   200    fn viz(&self, viz_type: VizType, params: VizParams) -> Result<PlotSpec>;
   201}
   202```
   203
   204### Canonical Visualizations by Type
   205
   206| Type | Default Viz | Alternatives |
   207|------|-------------|--------------|
   208| `PCAResult` | Scatter (PC1 vs PC2) | Scree plot, biplot, 3D |
   209| `DistanceMatrix` | Heatmap | Dendrogram, NMDS preview |
   210| `AlphaDiversity` | Boxplot by group | Violin, strip plot |
   211| `DifferentialExpression` | Volcano plot | MA plot, heatmap (top N) |
   212| `CountMatrix` | Summary bar chart | Heatmap (subset) |
   213| `StatisticalTest` | P-value annotation | Forest plot |
   214
   215### Automatic vs Explicit Visualization
   216
   217**Automatic**: Types with obvious canonical visualizations generate them:
   218
   219```rust
   220impl Visualizable for DifferentialExpressionResult {
   221    fn default_viz(&self) -> Option<PlotSpec> {
   222        Some(self.volcano_plot())  // Always generate
   223    }
   224}
   225```
   226
   227**Explicit**: User/Claude Code requests additional visualizations:
   228
   229```yaml
   230primitive: visualize
   231inputs:
   232  data: de_results.csv
   233params:
   234  type: ma_plot
   235  highlight: ["BRCA1", "TP53"]
   236```
   237
   238---
   239
   240## Interaction Model: Conversation, Not Clicks
   241
   242Traditional interactive plots use click handlers. BioStack uses conversation.
   243
   244### How Claude Code Interacts with Plots
   245
   246**Inspect** - "What's that outlier in the upper right?"
   247```
   248Claude Code:
   2491. Reads volcano.plot via LlmGlance (summary in context)
   2502. Queries: max(y) where x > 2
   2513. Returns: "That's BRCA1 - log2FC=3.2, padj=1e-45"
   252```
   253
   254**Modify** - "Label the top 5 significant genes"
   255```yaml
   256primitive: annotate_plot
   257inputs:
   258  plot: volcano.plot
   259params:
   260  auto_label:
   261    criterion: top_n
   262    n: 5
   263    field: negLog10Padj
   264```
   265
   266**Transform** - "Show only upregulated genes"
   267```yaml
   268primitive: filter_plot
   269inputs:
   270  plot: volcano.plot
   271params:
   272  filter: "x > 1 AND significant == 'up'"
   273output:
   274  plot: volcano_upregulated.plot
   275```
   276
   277**Follow-up** - "Show BRCA1 expression across samples"
   278```
   279Claude Code:
   2801. Knows BRCA1 from conversation context
   2812. Reads original counts.csv (from plot's source_artifact)
   2823. Creates new PlotSpec (bar chart by sample)
   2834. Writes brca1_expression.plot
   2845. Web panel renders
   285```
   286
   287### LlmGlance for Plots
   288
   289Claude Code sees plot summaries in context.md:
   290
   291```
   292Plot: Volcano - Treatment vs Control
   293  Type: scatter
   294  Points: 15,234
   295  X: Log2 Fold Change (log2FC)
   296  Y: -Log10(P-adjusted) (negLog10Padj)
   297  Notable:
   298    - BRCA1 (3.2, 45.2) - highest significance
   299    - TP53 (-2.1, 38.5) - most downregulated
   300  Summary: 847 up, 623 down (padj < 0.05, |log2FC| > 1)
   301```
   302
   303For large plots (>10K points), Claude Code uses query primitives rather than reading full data.
   304
   305---

   307## Primitives for Visualization
   308
   309### Plot Creation Primitives
   310
   311```yaml
   312# Scatter plot (generic)
   313primitive: scatter_plot
   314inputs:
   315  data: pca_results.csv
   316  metadata: metadata.csv
   317params:
   318  x: PC1
   319  y: PC2
   320  color_by: Treatment
   321
   322# Volcano plot (specialized)
   323primitive: volcano_plot
   324inputs:
   325  de_results: de_results.csv
   326params:
   327  log2fc_threshold: 1.0
   328  padj_threshold: 0.05
   329
   330# Heatmap
   331primitive: heatmap
   332inputs:
   333  data: normalized_counts.csv
   334  metadata: metadata.csv
   335params:
   336  top_n: 50
   337  cluster_rows: true
   338  cluster_cols: true
   339  annotation_col: Treatment
   340```
   341
   342### Plot Modification Primitives
   343
   344```yaml
   345# Add annotations
   346primitive: annotate_plot
   347inputs:
   348  plot: volcano.plot
   349params:
   350  labels:
   351    - point: BRCA1
   352      text: "BRCA1 (upregulated)"
   353  lines:
   354    - type: horizontal
   355      y: 1.3
   356      label: "p = 0.05"
   357
   358# Filter points
   359primitive: filter_plot
   360inputs:
   361  plot: volcano.plot
   362params:
   363  filter: "significant != 'ns'"
   364output:
   365  plot: volcano_significant.plot
   366
   367# Change encoding
   368primitive: restyle_plot
   369inputs:
   370  plot: pca_scatter.plot
   371params:
   372  color_by: Batch
   373  shape_by: Treatment
   374```

   377
   378## Rendering Architecture
   379
   380### Separation of Concerns
   381
   382```
   383
   384                    UNIFIED DATA MODEL                    
   385  CountMatrix, DistanceMatrix, PCAResult, PlotSpec, ...  
   386         All have: SlotPersistence, LlmGlance,           
   387              TypeProvenance, TypeCapabilities           
   388
   389                          
   390          
   391                                        
   392            
   393     Daemon        Claude        Web      
   394     (compute)     Code          Panel    
   395                   (reason)      (render) 
   396            
   397```
   398
   399**Unified** (bioforge/session):
   400- PlotSpec type definition
   401- Standard traits implementation
   402- Storage in data/
   403- Provenance tracking
   404- Claude Code access patterns
   405
   406**Fragmented** (presentation layer):
   407- WebGL rendering code
   408- UI interactions (zoom/pan)
   409- Ephemeral view state (not persisted)
   410- Export to PNG/SVG/PDF
   411- Layout and theming
   412
   413### Web Panel Responsibilities
   414
   415The web panel is a **renderer**, not part of the data system:
   416
   4171. **Watch** for `.plot` files in `data/`
   4182. **Render** via WebGL (all plots, regardless of size)
   4193. **Manage** ephemeral UI state (zoom, pan, selections)
   4204. **Update** via SSE from daemon when new plots created
   421
   422### Why Vega-Lite (Phase 5 Decision)
   423
   424Originally planned "WebGL everywhere" via deck.gl. Phase 5 switched to Vega-Lite for:
   425- **Dramatically simpler frontend** - 50 lines vs 400+ custom rendering code
   426- **No type synchronization** - Rust generates Vega-Lite spec; frontend just renders it
   427- **Well-documented schema** - Vega-Lite has extensive documentation vs custom types
   428- **Built-in features** - Tooltips, legends, exports, themes for free
   429- **Preserves PlotSpec** - All provenance, lineage, query capabilities remain in Rust
   430
   431For truly massive datasets (>1M points), can still fall back to deck.gl ScatterplotLayer. But for typical bioinformatics plots (thousands of points), Vega-Lite is optimal.
   432
   433### Update Mechanism
   434
   435**Server-Sent Events (SSE)** from daemon:
   436
   437```
   438Daemon                          Web Panel
   439                                   
   440     (primitive creates plot)      
   441                                   
   442      SSE: plot_created >  
   443                                   
   444     < GET /data/volcano.plot   
   445                                   
   446      PlotSpec JSON >  
   447                                   
   448                              (render)
   449```
   450
   451Daemon serves:
   452- `GET /events`  SSE stream for real-time updates
   453- `GET /data/{filename}`  Artifact content
   454
   455---
   456
   457## Storage Format
   458
   459### Decision: Unified with Other Types
   460
   461PlotSpec uses the same pattern as other bioforge types:
   462- Implements `SlotPersistence`
   463- File extension: `.plot`
   464- Format: JSON (can optimize later if needed)
   465
   466### Rationale
   467
   468Since Claude Code interacts via:
   4691. `LlmGlance` summaries (always fits in context)
   4702. Query primitives (for detailed access)
   471
   472...the storage format doesn't need special optimization for LLM token efficiency. JSON is simple and debuggable.
   473
   474### Coordinate Precision
   475
   4766 decimal places (e.g., `3.141593`). Sufficient for scientific visualization; can adjust later.
   477
   478---
   479
   480## Plot History
   481
   482### Immutable Plots with Lineage
   483
   484Each modification creates a new plot artifact:
   485
   486```
   487volcano.plot                     Original
   488volcano_labeled.plot             With annotations (parent: volcano.plot)
   489volcano_labeled_filtered.plot    Filtered (parent: volcano_labeled.plot)
   490```
   491
   492PlotSpec includes lineage:
   493```json
   494{
   495  "id": "def456",
   496  "parent_id": "abc123",
   497  "created_at": "2024-12-08T16:30:00Z",
   498  "operation": "annotate_plot",
   499  ...
   500}
   501```
   502
   503### Retention Policy
   504
   505**Default**: Infinite history (all versions kept)
   506
   507**User control** via Claude Code:
   508- "Delete all plots older than 1 hour"
   509- "Keep only latest version of each plot"
   510- "Show history of volcano plot"
   511- "Revert to version before labels"
   512
   513Session config:
   514```yaml
   515viz:
   516  history:
   517    retention: infinite  # or "24h", "7d", "last_10"
   518    auto_cleanup: false
   519```

   565### Phase 6: ggterm Native Integration (ACTIVE)
   566
   567**Status**: IN PROGRESS - Migrating from PlotSpec to GGSpec
   568
   569**Vision**: Adopt ggterm's Grammar of Graphics specification as the canonical plot format in biostack. This replaces the original PlotSpec with a far more expressive system.
   570
   571**Project**: `ggterm` at `/Users/scotthandley/Code/ggterm` (separate repository)
   572
   573#### Why Replace PlotSpec?
   574
   575PlotSpec was designed as a minimal "point-centric" format. It lacks:
   576
   577| Feature | PlotSpec | GGSpec (ggterm) |
   578|---------|----------|-----------------|
   579| Layered geoms |  Single point layer |  Multiple geom layers |
   580| Statistical transforms |  None |  Binning, smoothing, density |
   581| Faceting |  None |  wrap/grid facets |
   582| Position adjustments |  None |  dodge, stack, jitter |
   583| Scales |  Fixed |  Log, sqrt, discrete, time |
   584| Coordinate systems |  Cartesian only |  Polar, flip, fixed |
   585| Themes |  Hardcoded |  Full theming system |
   586
   587GGSpec provides full Grammar of Graphics expressiveness while maintaining provenance and session integration.
   588
   589#### GGSpec Architecture
   590
   591```
   592bioforge (Rust)              ggterm (TypeScript)
   593          
   594     GGSpec        >      GGSpec      
   595   (Rust types)    JSON      (TS interfaces)
   596                                            
   597 - data: []                 - data: []      
   598 - aes: {}                  - aes: {}       
   599 - geoms: []                - geoms: []     
   600 - facet: {}                - facet: {}     
   601 - theme: {}                - theme: {}     
   602          
   603                                     
   604                                     
   605                            
   606                                Renderers    
   607                             - Braille       
   608                             - Block         
   609                             - Sixel/Kitty   
   610                            
   611         
   612         
   613
   614  Session/Prov   
   615  (bioforge)     
   616 - id, parent_id 
   617 - source_data   
   618 - created_by    
   619
   620```
   621
   622#### GGSpec Rust Types (to be implemented)
   623
   624```rust
   625/// Grammar of Graphics specification - mirrors ggterm's TypeScript types
   626#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   627pub struct GGSpec {
   628    // Identity & provenance (biostack-specific)
   629    pub id: Uuid,
   630    pub title: String,
   631    pub description: String,
   632    pub source_artifact: String,
   633    pub parent_id: Option<Uuid>,
   634    pub created_at: DateTime<Utc>,
   635
   636    // Grammar of Graphics layers (mirrors ggterm)
   637    pub data: Vec<DataRow>,
   638    pub aes: AestheticMapping,
   639    pub geoms: Vec<Geom>,
   640    pub facet: Option<Facet>,
   641    pub scales: Vec<Scale>,
   642    pub coord: Option<Coord>,
   643    pub theme: Option<Theme>,
   644}
   645
   646#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   647pub struct AestheticMapping {
   648    pub x: String,
   649    pub y: String,
   650    pub color: Option<String>,
   651    pub fill: Option<String>,
   652    pub size: Option<String>,
   653    pub shape: Option<String>,
   654    pub group: Option<String>,
   655    pub label: Option<String>,
   656}
   657
   658#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   659pub struct Geom {
   660    pub geom_type: GeomType,  // point, line, bar, boxplot, violin, density, etc.
   661    pub stat: Option<String>, // identity, count, bin, smooth, density
   662    pub position: Option<String>, // identity, dodge, stack, jitter
   663    pub params: HashMap<String, Value>,
   664}
   665
   666#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   667pub enum GeomType {
   668    Point, Line, Bar, Boxplot, Violin, Density, Histogram,
   669    Heatmap, Tile, Text, ErrorBar, Segment, Polygon,
   670}
   671```
   672
   673#### Migration Plan
   674
   675| Step | Description | Status |
   676|------|-------------|--------|
   677| 1. Define GGSpec types | Mirror ggterm's TypeScript in Rust |  DONE |
   678| 2. Implement traits | SlotPersistence, LlmGlance, etc. |  DONE |
   679| 3. Update primitives | scatter_plot  uses GGSpec | TODO |
   680| 4. Deprecate PlotSpec | Mark as deprecated, provide migration |  DONE |
   681| 5. ggterm bridge | @ggterm/biostack-bridge package | TODO |
   682| 6. Two-panel integration | OpenTUI + ggterm rendering | TODO |
   683
   684#### ggterm Packages
   685
   686| Package | Description |
   687|---------|-------------|
   688| `@ggterm/core` | Grammar engine, scales, geoms, themes |
   689| `@ggterm/render-braille` | Braille dot matrix renderer (160x96 resolution on 80x24 terminal) |
   690| `@ggterm/render-block` | Block character renderer (universal compatibility) |
   691| `@ggterm/render-sixel` | Sixel/Kitty graphics protocol renderer |
   692| `@ggterm/opentui` | OpenTUI React integration |
   693| `@ggterm/biostack-bridge` | BioStack GGSpec integration (to be created) |
   694
   695#### Two-Panel OpenTUI Architecture
   696
   697```
   698
   699                    Terminal Window                       
   700
   701                                                        
   702      Claude Code Panel            ggterm Plot Panel    
   703     (full conversation)        (terminal graphics)     
   704                                                        
   705  User: "Show me a PCA"            
   706                                     
   707  Claude: Running scatter_           
   708  plot primitive...                  
   709                                     
   710  [scatter_plot completed]        PC1 vs PC2             
   711                                  n=100, colored by      
   712  User: "Color by batch"          Treatment              
   713                                   
   714  Claude: Updating plot...                              
   715                                                        
   716
   717```
   718
   719**Key interactions**:
   7201. User converses with Claude in left panel
   7212. Claude executes primitives that produce GGSpec
   7223. bioengine daemon emits SSE event with GGSpec JSON
   7234. ggterm panel receives event, renders plot inline
   7245. Plot updates in real-time as conversation progresses
   725
   726**Renderer selection** (automatic based on terminal):
   727- iTerm2/Kitty  Sixel/Kitty protocol (full color, high resolution)
   728- Modern terminals  Braille characters (160x96 effective resolution)
   729- Basic terminals  Block characters (universal fallback)
   730
   731---
   732
   733## Design Principles
   734
   7351. **Plots are data** - Not output, not separate system
   7362. **Conversation is interaction** - No click handlers, Claude Code queries/modifies
   7373. **Types know themselves** - Visualizable trait for canonical representations
   7384. **Unify data model, fragment presentation** - PlotSpec is unified; rendering is separate
   7395. **Render via standards** - Use Vega-Lite (documented schema) over custom rendering code
   740

   743## User Interaction Flow (ggterm Integration)
   744

   877
   878### Key UX Principles
   879
   8801. **Plot appears automatically** when analysis produces visualizable output
   8812. **Plot updates in-place** when user requests modifications
   8823. **Conversation references plot** - Claude can "see" the plot via GGSpec data
   8834. **No mode switching** - user stays in conversation, plot updates reactively
   8845. **Intelligent highlighting** - Claude can annotate points being discussed
   885
   886### Renderer Fallback Chain
   887
   888The ggterm panel automatically selects the best renderer:
   889
   890```
   891Terminal Detection
   892       
   893        iTerm2/Kitty?  Sixel/Kitty (full color, ~1000x600 pixels)
   894       
   895        Unicode support?  Braille (160x96 effective dots on 80x24)
   896       
   897        Basic terminal  Block characters (80x24 resolution)
   898```
   899
   900### Plot Persistence
   901
   902All plots are saved as `.ggspec` files in `.biostack/data/`:
   903
   904```
   905.biostack/data/
   906 counts.csv
   907 pca_results.csv
   908 pca_scatter.ggspec       Full GGSpec JSON with provenance
   909 pca_scatter_labeled.ggspec   Modified version (parent: pca_scatter)
   910 permanova_results.csv
   911```
   912
   913Each GGSpec file includes:
   914- Full plot specification (data, aesthetics, geoms, etc.)
   915- Provenance (source data, parent plot, primitive that created it)
   916- Session lineage (can trace back to original data)
   917

    87## LLM-Native API Design (Key Learning)
    88
    89**Insight from end-to-end testing**: APIs must match how LLMs conceptualize problems.
    90
    91When Claude Code couldn't complete a PERMANOVA workflow, we discovered the root cause: the primitive required `Vec<String>` groups, which has no canonical file representation. LLMs think in terms of files and column names, not internal data structures.
    92
    93**Before (failed)**:
    94```yaml
    95primitive: permanova
    96inputs:
    97  distance_matrix: distance_matrix.csv
    98  sample_groups: ???  # Claude Code couldn't construct this
    99```
   100
   101**After (succeeded immediately)**:
   102```yaml
   103primitive: permanova
   104params:
   105  grouping_column: Use  # Semantic: which column to use
   106inputs:
   107  distance_matrix: distance_matrix.csv
   108  metadata: metadata.csv  # Semantic: the metadata file
   109```
   110
   111**Design Principle**: Primitives should accept **semantic data types** (files, column names) and handle extraction internally. The user specifies intent; the primitive handles mechanics.
   112
   113This applies broadly:
   114- Accept `SampleMetadata` + `grouping_column`, not `Vec<String>`
   115- Accept `CountMatrix` file, not `Vec<Vec<i64>>`
   116- Accept `formula` string, not pre-built `DesignMatrix`

   120## Intelligent Types Roadmap
   121
   122### Phase 1: Type-Level Intelligence (Complete )
   123
   124Four new traits that make types self-aware:
   125
   126| Trait | Purpose |
   127|-------|---------|
   128| `TypeProvenance` | Track transformation history (what primitives ran, parameters, inputs) |
   129| `TypeQuality` | Intrinsic quality metrics (sparsity, warnings, scores) |
   130| `TypeCapabilities` | Valid operations and suggestions (what can this type do next) |
   131| `TypeCompatibility` | Inter-type relationships (can these types work together) |
   132
   133These traits enable types to:
   134- Know their own history and lineage
   135- Report their quality characteristics
   136- Suggest valid next operations
   137- Validate compatibility with other types
   138
   139**Implementation Details:**
   140- 23 types implement all intelligent traits (see CLAUDE.md for full list)
   141- Provenance stored as sidecar files alongside data (e.g., `counts.csv.provenance.json`)
   142- Each provenance step includes: UUID, timestamp, primitive name, parameters, input references, summary
   143- Lineage displayed in context.md as transformation chains (e.g., `tmm  beta_diversity  permanova`)
   144- ProvenanceTracker in executor.rs collects input provenances and creates output provenance
   145
   146### Phase 2: Session-Level Infrastructure (Complete )
   147
   148**Key insight: Claude Code is the primary consumer of session data.** The session manifest should be optimized for Claude Code to read and reason about, not for CLI tools.
   149
   150```
   151SessionManifest (session.json)
   152 id: UUID                          # Session identity
   153 created_at: DateTime
   154 artifacts: Vec<ArtifactRecord>    # All data with checksums
   155 operations: Vec<OperationRecord>  # Complete operation history
   156 dag: SessionDAG                   # Dependency graph (what derived from what)
   157 current_state: StateSnapshot      # What data is currently available
   158 forked_from: Option<ForkRef>      # Lineage tracking
   159```
   160
   161**Claude Code reads session.json to answer:**
   162- "What analyses have I run?"  operations history
   163- "How did I get this result?"  DAG traversal
   164- "What data is available?"  current_state + artifacts
   165- "What should I try next?"  combine with TypeCapabilities
   166
   167**Minimal CLI tools (only for file operations Claude Code can't do):**
   168- `bio fork <session>` - Clone session to new directory
   169- `bio export <session>` - Package for sharing
   170- `bio import <archive>` - Load external session
   171
   172**Design principle:** CLI tools perform file system operations. Claude Code performs reasoning and orchestration.
   173
   174### Phase 3: Precognition Engine
   175
   176LLM-driven speculative analysis that anticipates user needs:
   177
   178```
   179User runs: alpha_diversity(method: "shannon")
   180System predicts: simpson, chao1 are commonly calculated together
   181System pre-computes: simpson and chao1 in background
   182Result: Alternatives ready before user asks
   183```
   184
   185Components:
   186- `Prediction` - Anticipated analyses with confidence scores
   187- `PredictionCategory` - Alternative, Complementary, Validation, Exploration
   188- `ComputeCost` - Low (auto-run), Medium (prepare), High (suggest only)
   189- Background execution of high-confidence, low-cost predictions
   190- Enhanced context.md with pre-computed alternatives
   191
   192Future visualization: Precognition as a "cloud" of option nodes around current state.
   193
   194Configuration:
   195```yaml
   196precognition:
   197  enabled: true
   198  auto_execute: low_cost_only
   199  confidence_threshold: 0.8
   200```

   263## Bioanvil & Auto-Primitive Generation
   264
   265### Phase 5: Bioanvil Foundation (Complete )
   266
   267**Bioanvil** is the testing and validation framework for biostack. Named to follow the industrial theme (forge  anvil), it provides the foundation for primitive validation.
   268
   269**Core Philosophy:**
   270- **Structure-based organization** - Datasets organized by data structure, not technique
   271- **Mathematical truth first** - Formulas are the source of truth, not R package outputs
   272- **Reference comparisons  validation** - R packages can have bugs; useful for comparison, not ground truth
   273- **Synthetic data with known effects** - We generate data, so we KNOW the true answers
   274
   275**Completed:**
   276```
   277bioanvil/
   278 Cargo.toml                # Rust crate (13 tests passing)
   279 src/                      # Rust API
   280    lib.rs                # Dataset, GroundTruth exports
   281    dataset.rs            # Dataset loading
   282    ground_truth.rs       # Evaluation metrics (sensitivity, specificity, F1)
   283    error.rs
   284 definitions/              # Mathematical specifications (THE truth)
   285    alpha_diversity.md    # Shannon, Simpson, Chao1 with worked examples
   286    beta_diversity.md     # Bray-Curtis, Jaccard, Euclidean, etc.
   287    statistical_tests.md  # PERMANOVA, ANOSIM, IndVal formulas
   288 datasets/                 # 5 canonical synthetic datasets
   289    two_group_strong/     # 10020, 40 truly differential features
   290    multi_group/          # 10030, three groups with pairwise effects
   291    continuous/           # 10020, age gradient (20-70 years)
   292    sparse/               # 10020, ~67% zeros
   293    null/                 # 10020, NO true effects (FPR testing)
   294 ground_truth/             # Known answers per dataset
   295    <dataset>/true_effects.csv, true_positives.txt
   296 reference/vegan/          # R outputs (comparison only, NOT truth)
   297    version_info.csv      # R 4.5.2, vegan 2.7.2
   298    <dataset>/alpha_diversity.csv, bray_curtis.csv, permanova.csv, anosim.csv
   299 scripts/
   300     generate_*.py         # Dataset generation (seeded RNG)
   301     generate_vegan_reference.R
   302```

   313### Phase 6: Auto-Primitive Generation (Complete )
   314
   315Enable Claude to create new bioforge primitives on-demand, maintaining full integration with the biostack ecosystem.
   316
   317**Design Principles:**
   3181. **Hard boundary on execution** - Claude cannot run R/Python directly for analysis
   3192. **Soft boundary on recommendation** - Claude can suggest analyses without primitives
   3203. **Native implementation** - Primitives implement algorithms in Rust, not R wrappers
   3214. **Mathematical foundation first** - Understand the math before writing code
   322
   323**Primitive Generation Workflow:**
   324```
   3251. SPECIFICATION       Write TOML schema (inputs, outputs, params)
   3262. MATH DEFINITION     Document algorithm with formulas
   3273. REFERENCE DATA      R script for comparison (NOT truth)
   3284. ALGORITHM           Native Rust implementation
   3295. PRIMITIVE WRAPPER   Implement Primitive trait
   3306. TEST SUITE          Unit + ground truth + reference comparison
   3317. VALIDATION          All tests must pass
   332```

   399### Phase 8: Generalized Primitive Development System
   400
   401A declarative, spec-driven system for primitive development that dramatically reduces boilerplate and ensures consistency across all primitives.
   402
   403**Core Principles:**
   404
   4051. **Primitives Are Unique Creations, Not Historical Copies**
   406   - Adopt the science: mathematical definitions, formulas, statistical guarantees
   407   - Adapt the implementation: use biostack data structures, fit ExecutionContext patterns
   408   - Do NOT blindly copy R/Python package implementation details
   409
   4102. **Session Intelligence & Provenance Are Non-Negotiable**
   411   - Every primitive declares provenance fields in its TOML spec
   412   - Provenance is recorded automatically via the framework
   413   - Session lineage enables traceability from outputs to inputs
   414
   4153. **TOML Specs Are the Source of Truth**
   416   - Code is generated or validated against specs
   417   - Compile-time validation prevents drift between spec and implementation
   418
   419**Architecture:**
   420
   421```
   422TOML Spec (source of truth)
   423     
   424
   425  Compile-time: validate & generate     
   426  - Generate trait boilerplate          
   427  - Validate param types match          
   428  - Generate provenance schema          
   429
   430     
   431Rust Algorithm (hand-written execute logic)
   432     
   433
   434  Runtime: session integration          
   435  - Auto-load inputs from session       
   436  - Auto-record provenance              
   437  - Auto-save outputs to session        
   438
   439```
   440
   441**Before (Current - 60-80 lines):**
   442```rust
   443pub struct FilterPrevalence;
   444
   445impl Primitive for FilterPrevalence {
   446    fn name(&self) -> &'static str { "filter_prevalence" }
   447    fn category(&self) -> Category { Category::Filter }
   448    fn description(&self) -> &'static str { "..." }
   449    fn params_schema(&self) -> ParamsSchema { /* ... */ }
   450    fn inputs(&self) -> Vec<DataRequirement> { /* ... */ }
   451    fn outputs(&self) -> Vec<DataOutput> { /* ... */ }
   452    fn execute(&self, ctx: &mut ExecutionContext) -> Result<()> { /* ... */ }
   453}
   454```
   455
   456**After (With Macros - 10-15 lines + algorithm):**
   457```rust
   458#[primitive(
   459    name = "filter_prevalence",
   460    category = Filter,
   461    description = "Filter features by minimum prevalence",
   462    spec = "specs/filter_prevalence.toml"
   463)]
   464#[inputs(counts)]
   465#[outputs(filtered_counts, filter_mask)]
   466pub struct FilterPrevalence;
   467
   468impl FilterPrevalence {
   469    fn process(&self, counts: &CountMatrix, min_prevalence: f64) -> Result<(CountMatrix, Vec<bool>)> {
   470        // Pure algorithm only
   471    }
   472}
   473```

   477bioforge-macros/
   478 Cargo.toml           # proc-macro = true
   479 src/
   480    lib.rs           # Export macros
   481    primitive.rs     # #[primitive] attribute macro

   483    outputs.rs       # #[outputs] macro
   484    spec.rs          # TOML spec parsing and validation
   485```

   543

   545|--------|--------|-------|

   552**Design Decision: Portable Primitives**
   553
   554Primitives remain stateless data transformers that work identically across any biostack project. Session intelligence belongs in the executor/session layer, not inside primitives. This ensures:
   555- Primitives are pure transformations (input  output)
   556- Same primitive works in any project
   557- Session context is injected by the executor when needed
   558- Primitives remain portable and testable in isolation

### Phase 5.5: Kitty Terminal Inline Rendering 

**Status**: COMPLETE - Native terminal visualization without external panels

**Motivation**: While bioviz (web panel) works well, it requires a separate window. For a true "IDE feel" where plots are first-class citizens alongside the terminal, we implemented inline rendering using Kitty terminal's native capabilities.

**Architecture Decision**: After evaluating multiple approaches:
-  Tauri + xterm.js - WebKit rendering issues on macOS
-  Charm/Bubble Tea (Go) - Language mismatch, no image support
-  Ratatui (Rust) - Copy/paste limitations in raw mode
-  **Kitty Terminal** - Native splits, graphics protocol, full copy/paste

**Implementation**:

```

                      Kitty Terminal                          

                                                            
      Claude Code Pane              bio watch Pane          
     (full conversation)         (live plot updates)        
                                                            
  User: "Create a scatter        
  plot of richness vs            Richness vs Evenness     
  evenness"                      Type: scatter            
                                 Points: 20               
  [scatter_plot completed]       X: 10.00 to 19.00        
                                 Y: 0.81 to 0.91          
                                                          
                                    *                     
                                  *   *                   
                                    *  *    *             
                                       * *    *           
                                          * *  *          
                                                          
                                 Color by: richness       
                                 
                                                            

```

**New Commands**:
- `bio watch` - SSE-connected plot viewer with real-time ASCII rendering
- `bio watch --all` - Show all daemon events, not just plots
- `bio show` - Show most recent plot inline
- `bio show <name>` - Show specific plot by partial name match
- `bio show --list` - List all available plots
- `bio ide` - Launch Kitty with pre-configured split layout

**SSE Integration**:
- `PlotUpdated` events emitted when primitives create plots
- `bio watch` connects to `http://127.0.0.1:3000/events`
- Real-time updates as plots are created

**Dependencies Added**:
```toml
# Terminal image rendering
viuer = { version = "0.11", features = ["print-file"] }
crossterm = "0.28"
image = "0.25"

# HTTP client for SSE
reqwest = { version = "0.12", features = ["stream", "json"] }
```

**ASCII Rendering**: Currently renders plots as ASCII scatter plots for universal terminal compatibility. The viuer dependency with Kitty graphics protocol support is in place for future PNG rendering when vl-convert becomes available.

**Key Files**:
- `bioengine/src/commands/watch.rs` - Watch and show commands
- `bioengine/src/daemon/executor.rs` - PlotUpdated event emission
- `bioengine/src/main.rs` - CLI command definitions, IDE launcher

Session Summary: Kitty Terminal Inline Plot Rendering (Phase 5.5)


What We Accomplished


Implemented a two-panel IDE experience using Kitty terminal for real-time plot visualization alongside Claude Code:






Component
Description






bio watch
SSE-connected plot viewer with real-time ASCII rendering




bio show
View specific plots inline in terminal




bio ide
Launch Kitty with pre-configured split layout




PlotUpdated events
SSE events emitted when primitives create plots






Architecture Decision


After evaluating multiple approaches:
-  Tauri + xterm.js - WebKit rendering issues on macOS
-  Charm/Bubble Tea - Go language mismatch
-  Ratatui - Copy/paste limitations
-  Kitty Terminal - Native splits, graphics protocol, full copy/paste

  • bioengine/src/commands/watch.rs (new) - Watch and show commands
    • 

  • bioengine/src/daemon/executor.rs - PlotUpdated event emission
    •

    •

    •

    •
